data.content:
In .NET MAUI, those `Application`-level overrides were moved to the **`Window`** class. Override `CreateWindow()` in your `App` class and use `Window` lifecycle events:

| Xamarin.Forms | .NET MAUI `Window` |
|---|---|
| `OnStart()` | `Created` |
| `OnSleep()` | `Stopped` / `Deactivated` |
| `OnResume()` | `Resumed` / `Activated` |

**Option 1 — Subscribe to events:**

```csharp
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
{
    var window = new Window(new AppShell());

    window.Created += (s, e) => { /* OnStart logic */ };
    window.Stopped += (s, e) => { /* OnSleep logic */ };
    window.Resumed += (s, e) => { /* OnResume logic */ };

    return window;
}
```

**Option 2 — Subclass `Window` and override methods:**

```csharp
public class MyWindow : Window
{
    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnCreated() { /* OnStart */ }
    protected override void OnStopped() { /* OnSleep */ }
    protected override void OnResumed() { /* OnResume */ }
}
```

Then in `App`:

```csharp
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    => new MyWindow(new AppShell());
```

`Deactivated`/`Activated` fire on focus changes; `Stopped`/`Resumed` are closer to the old `OnSleep`/`OnResume` semantics (app fully backgrounded/foregrounded).
